amdgpu: uvd_v4_2 — region sizes at slot 0 + k=1 clock divider (v76d-β-2-A8)

Two combined changes:

== A7c part: write actual region SIZES at region 2[0] and region 3[0] ==
A7 (0047, now disabled) wrote 0x00000001 at those slots and caused a
regression — cache no longer reached Sony's synced pattern. That
proved the fw reads those slots; the natural interpretation is they
hold SIZE FIELDS, not magic flags. Sony's userspace would write the
actual region sizes there.

  *region2[0] = PS4_UVD_REGION2_SIZE  (0x124000 = 1168 KB heap)
  *region3[0] = PS4_UVD_REGION3_SIZE  (0x4000   = 16 KB msgq)

== A9 part: change VCPU clock divider k from 4 to 1 ==
Sony reads ctx[+0x40] & 0xf into the LMI VCPU CACHE VMID register
(0x3d3c) and several index/data subregs. The value is a clock
divider hint (per Ghidra plate comment on gladius variant). We
hardcoded k=4 as a mid-range guess.

A6 showed VCPU alive but never asserts STATUS bit 1. One possible
cause: VCPU clock running too slow → init routine times out
internally before completing. k=1 is the fastest division.

Combined experiment. If STATUS bit 1 sets → at least one of the two
worked. Narrow down in follow-up.

Expected hardware signals:
  ✅ UVD initialized successfully — combo works (narrow down which)
  🟡 Different sample table — fw advanced; learn next step
  ❌ Same STATUS=0x4 stall — neither was the gate; pivot to
     reviewing test-baikal log or trying different k values

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>

--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/uvd_v4_2.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/uvd_v4_2.c
@@ -519,6 +519,21 @@
 	memcpy(mirror_cpu_addr, adev->uvd.fw->data + ucode_offset, ucode_size);

 	/*
+	 * v76d-β-2-A8 (A7c part): write the SIZE of each region at its
+	 * start. A7 (now disabled) wrote 0x00000001 there and broke fw
+	 * cache fill — that regression proved fw reads these slots. The
+	 * natural interpretation is they're SIZE fields, not flags.
+	 * Sony's userspace would write region2_size and region3_size
+	 * there before the VCPU release. Try that.
+	 */
+	*(u32 *)(mirror_cpu_addr + PS4_UVD_REGION1_SIZE) =
+		PS4_UVD_REGION2_SIZE;	/* heap_size at region2[0] */
+	*(u32 *)(mirror_cpu_addr + PS4_UVD_REGION1_SIZE + PS4_UVD_REGION2_SIZE) =
+		PS4_UVD_REGION3_SIZE;	/* msgq_size at region3[0] */
+	DRM_INFO("ps4 uvd: A8 wrote sizes — region2[0]=0x%lx, region3[0]=0x%lx\n",
+		 PS4_UVD_REGION2_SIZE, PS4_UVD_REGION3_SIZE);
+
+	/*
 	 * Rebind GART at 0x300000000 for the full 3-region span (3.1 MB).
 	 * Overwrites the dummy bind from gmc_v7_0_gart_enable (v76d-β-2-A).
 	 * The VC1..VC15 flat walk now finds:
@@ -635,12 +650,15 @@
 	/*
 	 * VCPU clock divider. Sony reads ctx[+0x40] which is set
 	 * elsewhere in their kernel — we don't have access to it here.
-	 * Use k = 4 as a mid-range guess; this register family controls
-	 * VCPU PLL division. If we see weird boot timing or hangs,
-	 * adjust here (range 1..15 is the field width).
+	 *
+	 * v76d-β-2-A8 (A9 part): try k = 1 (fastest divider) instead of
+	 * the previous k = 4. A6 showed VCPU is alive but never
+	 * asserts STATUS bit 1; one possibility is the VCPU clock is
+	 * running too slow at k=4 and the fw's init routine times out
+	 * internally. k=1 is the fastest division (full clock).
 	 */
 	{
-		uint32_t k = 4;
+		uint32_t k = 1;

 		WREG32(0x3d3c, k);
